"# Chapter 6: Weight & Embodiment

A falling brick and a falling petal both obey gravity, yet one crashes down while the other drifts. The difference isn't **what** happens — it's **how the motion feels** against time. This chapter drills the **:embodiment regime** — the parameter space that makes an entity read as dense or airy, settled or skittish, grounded or floating.

Weight isn't mass alone. It's the interplay of gravity scale, drag, settle time, and how hard something fights to stop. We'll take a single motion primitive — a drop, a toss, a glide — and tune its **feel** from anvil-heavy to dandelion-seed light.

By the end, you'll author motion that **reads** as embodiment: a boulder that thuds, a feather that wafts, a sack of grain that sags into rest.

---

## The Gravity Baseline

Every entity has a **gravity scale** — a multiplier on the world's downward pull. Scale of `1.0` is normal Earth weight. Scale of `0.0` is weightless. Scale of `3.0` is three times heavier.

We'll start with three identical entities, each dropped from the same height, differing only in gravity scale.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((brick (world/spawn 'rect :x 50 :y 200 :color \"#8B4513\" :label \"brick\"))
      (ball  (world/spawn 'circle :x 150 :y 200 :color \"#FFD700\" :label \"ball\"))
      (petal (world/spawn 'petal :x 250 :y 200 :color \"#FFB6C1\" :label \"petal\")))
  (entity/gravity-scale! brick 2.0)
  (entity/gravity-scale! ball 1.0)
  (entity/gravity-scale! petal 0.3)
  (world/step 120))
```

[VISUAL: Three entities fall. The brick plummets and hits hard. The ball drops at normal speed. The petal floats down lazily, barely accelerating.]

The brick's scale of `2.0` doubles gravity's tug. The petal's `0.3` makes it fall gently, as if the air itself is thick. Same world, same floor — different **embodiment**.

---

## Drag: The Invisible Thickness of Air

Gravity scale sets how **hard** an entity falls. **Drag** sets how much the air resists. High drag makes motion feel like it's moving through honey. Zero drag is a vacuum.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((stone (world/spawn 'rect :x 80 :y 250 :color \"#696969\" :label \"stone\"))
      (leaf  (world/spawn 'leaf :x 200 :y 250 :color \"#90EE90\" :label \"leaf\")))
  (entity/gravity-scale! stone 1.5)
  (entity/drag! stone 0.01)
  (entity/gravity-scale! leaf 0.4)
  (entity/drag! leaf 0.8)
  (world/step 150))
```

[VISUAL: The stone falls fast and clean — little drag, heavy gravity. The leaf tumbles slowly, its velocity damped by thick drag, drifting rather than plummeting.]

Drag isn't friction with a surface — it's **velocity damping**, the force that bleeds speed as an entity moves through space. A petal has high drag. A cannonball has almost none.

---

## Bounce: How Hard the Landing Reads

When an entity hits the floor, **bounce** controls how much energy returns. A rubber ball bounces high (`bounce: 0.9`). A sack of sand doesn't bounce at all (`bounce: 0.0`).

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((rubber (world/spawn 'circle :x 100 :y 300 :color \"#FF6347\" :label \"rubber\"))
      (clay   (world/spawn 'circle :x 200 :y 300 :color \"#8B7355\" :label \"clay\")))
  (entity/bounce! rubber 0.85)
  (entity/bounce! clay 0.1)
  (world/step 180))
```

[VISUAL: The rubber ball bounces high, again and again, losing a bit of height each time. The clay ball hits the floor and barely rebounds, settling almost immediately.]

Bounce is **restitution** — the fraction of velocity reversed on collision. High bounce feels springy, alive. Low bounce feels dense, final.

---

## The Settle Curve

An entity doesn't just stop — it **settles** into rest. The settle time is how long it takes to absorb the last wobbles, the final micro-bounces, the drift toward stillness.

Here we toss two entities upward and let them land. Same initial velocity, different settle behavior.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((quick (world/spawn 'rect :x 120 :y 200 :color \"#4682B4\" :label \"quick\"))
      (slow  (world/spawn 'rect :x 220 :y 200 :color \"#DDA0DD\" :label \"slow\")))
  (entity/set-vel! quick 0 -80)
  (entity/set-vel! slow 0 -80)
  (entity/bounce! quick 0.3)
  (entity/drag! quick 0.5)
  (entity/bounce! slow 0.6)
  (entity/drag! slow 0.05)
  (world/step 200))
```

[VISUAL: Both entities rise and fall. The quick one settles fast — low bounce, high drag. The slow one takes longer, bouncing several times, each bounce smaller, drifting into rest.]

Settle is a **feel regime**, not a single knob. It's the sum of bounce, drag, and friction. A heavy sack settles fast. A hollow tin can rattles and rolls.

---

## Mass: The Anchor in Motion

Mass affects how forces **push** an entity. A light entity accelerates quickly under the same impulse. A heavy entity resists, moving sluggishly.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)
(world/wind! 30 0)

(let ((paper (world/spawn 'rect :x 50 :y 150 :color \"#FFFACD\" :label \"paper\"))
      (crate (world/spawn 'rect :x 50 :y 180 :color \"#8B4513\" :label \"crate\")))
  (entity/mass! paper 0.2)
  (entity/mass! crate 5.0)
  (entity/drag! paper 0.3)
  (entity/drag! crate 0.1)
  (world/step 150))
```

[VISUAL: A steady rightward wind pushes both. The paper skitters and tumbles, blown across the floor. The crate inches slowly, barely moved by the same force.]

Mass is **inertia** — resistance to acceleration. High mass makes an entity feel planted, immovable. Low mass makes it skittish, twitchy, easily buffeted.

---

## Feather Fall: The Classic Light Embodiment

A feather doesn't drop — it **wafts**. Low gravity scale, high drag, almost no bounce. It drifts on invisible currents, turning lazily.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((feather (world/spawn 'feather :x 150 :y 300 :color \"#F0E68C\")))
  (entity/gravity-scale! feather 0.15)
  (entity/drag! feather 0.9)
  (entity/bounce! feather 0.0)
  (entity/mass! feather 0.1)
  (world/step 300))
```

[VISUAL: The feather descends in slow spirals, barely accelerating. It takes the full three seconds to reach the floor, swaying gently, then rests without a bounce.]

This is the **light embodiment** archetype: low gravity, high drag, zero bounce, minimal mass. Every parameter conspires toward drift.

---

## Anvil Drop: The Classic Heavy Embodiment

An anvil **plummets**. High gravity scale, low drag, low bounce. It hits the floor with a thud that reverberates.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((anvil (world/spawn 'rect :x 150 :y 300 :color \"#2F4F4F\" :label \"ANVIL\")))
  (entity/gravity-scale! anvil 2.5)
  (entity/drag! anvil 0.01)
  (entity/bounce! anvil 0.1)
  (entity/mass! anvil 10.0)
  (world/step 100))
```

[VISUAL: The anvil drops like a stone, accelerating hard. It hits the floor with barely a rebound, settling instantly. The motion reads as **heavy**.]

This is the **heavy embodiment** archetype: high gravity, low drag, low bounce, high mass. The parameters conspire toward weight.

---

## The Toss Test: Embodiment Under the Same Impulse

We toss three entities upward with identical initial velocity. Their embodiment determines the shape of the arc.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((rock   (world/spawn 'circle :x 80 :y 150 :color \"#708090\" :label \"rock\"))
      (ball   (world/spawn 'circle :x 150 :y 150 :color \"#FFA500\" :label \"ball\"))
      (bubble (world/spawn 'circle :x 220 :y 150 :color \"#E0FFFF\" :label \"bubble\")))
  (entity/set-vel! rock 0 -100)
  (entity/gravity-scale! rock 1.5)
  (entity/drag! rock 0.02)
  
  (entity/set-vel! ball 0 -100)
  (entity/gravity-scale! ball 1.0)
  (entity/drag! ball 0.05)
  
  (entity/set-vel! bubble 0 -100)
  (entity/gravity-scale! bubble 0.3)
  (entity/drag! bubble 0.7)
  
  (world/step 200))
```

[VISUAL: The rock rises quickly but falls hard — a tight, fast parabola. The ball traces a smooth arc. The bubble floats upward, slows, hangs, then drifts down languidly.]

Same impulse, three **feels**. The toss test is a litmus for embodiment — it reveals how an entity fights gravity and air.

---

## Friction: Sliding to Rest

When an entity lands on the floor, **friction** bleeds horizontal velocity. High friction stops sliding fast. Zero friction is ice.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((hockey (world/spawn 'circle :x 50 :y 120 :color \"#000080\" :label \"puck\"))
      (tire   (world/spawn 'circle :x 50 :y 160 :color \"#2F4F4F\" :label \"tire\")))
  (entity/set-vel! hockey 80 0)
  (entity/friction! hockey 0.01)
  
  (entity/set-vel! tire 80 0)
  (entity/friction! tire 0.95)
  
  (world/step 200))
```

[VISUAL: The hockey puck glides almost frictionlessly, coasting across the floor. The tire stops abruptly, dragged down by high friction.]

Friction is **surface resistance** — the force that opposes sliding. A puck on ice has almost none. A tire on asphalt has plenty.

---

## The Sack of Grain: Sag and Settle

A sack of grain doesn't bounce. It **sags** into the floor, absorbing impact, settling with a soft thud.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((sack (world/spawn 'sack :x 150 :y 280 :color \"#D2B48C\" :label \"grain\")))
  (entity/gravity-scale! sack 1.2)
  (entity/drag! sack 0.3)
  (entity/bounce! sack 0.0)
  (entity/mass! sack 3.0)
  (entity/friction! sack 0.8)
  (world/step 120))
```

[VISUAL: The sack drops, hits the floor without bouncing, and spreads slightly as if settling under its own weight. It reads as **soft and heavy**.]

Zero bounce, moderate drag, high friction — the sack embodies **inelastic mass**. It doesn't fight gravity; it surrenders to it.

---

## The Balloon: Rising Against Gravity

A helium balloon has **negative effective gravity** — it rises instead of falls. We model this with a gravity scale less than zero.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((balloon (world/spawn 'circle :x 150 :y 150 :color \"#FF69B4\" :label \"balloon\")))
  (entity/gravity-scale! balloon -0.4)
  (entity/drag! balloon 0.6)
  (entity/mass! balloon 0.1)
  (world/step 200))
```

[VISUAL: The balloon floats upward gently, slowed by drag. It rises at a steady, lazy pace, bobbing slightly.]

Negative gravity scale is **buoyancy**. The entity is lighter than the medium it moves through. Drag keeps it from accelerating infinitely.

---

## The Marble Roll: Friction and Rolling Drag

A marble rolls down a slope, friction and drag conspiring to control its speed.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((marble (world/spawn 'circle :x 50 :y 250 :color \"#B0C4DE\" :label \"marble\")))
  (entity/set-vel! marble 60 0)
  (entity/gravity-scale! marble 1.0)
  (entity/friction! marble 0.15)
  (entity/drag! marble 0.05)
  (entity/bounce! marble 0.4)
  (world/step 200))
```

[VISUAL: The marble rolls across the floor, gradually slowing as friction saps momentum. It bounces slightly when it encounters any unevenness, but mostly glides to a stop.]

Rolling is **horizontal motion under friction**. The marble's bounce is low enough to keep it grounded, but high enough to feel alive.

---

## The Dropped Vase: Fragile Embodiment

A vase is heavy but brittle. It falls hard, bounces once (low restitution), then settles fast.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((vase (world/spawn 'vase :x 150 :y 280 :color \"#FFDAB9\" :label \"ceramic\")))
  (entity/gravity-scale! vase 1.3)
  (entity/drag! vase 0.05)
  (entity/bounce! vase 0.15)
  (entity/mass! vase 2.0)
  (entity/friction! vase 0.7)
  (world/step 100))
```

[VISUAL: The vase drops fast, hits the floor with a single small bounce, then settles immediately. The low bounce reads as **brittle** — it doesn't spring back.]

Fragile embodiment: moderate mass, low drag, very low bounce. The vase **thuds** rather than bounces.

---

## The Dandelion Seed: Maximum Lightness

A dandelion seed is the extreme of light embodiment. Nearly weightless, high drag, carried by the slightest breeze.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)
(world/wind! 20 0)

(let ((seed (world/spawn 'seed :x 50 :y 250 :color \"#FFFACD\")))
  (entity/gravity-scale! seed 0.05)
  (entity/drag! seed 0.95)
  (entity/mass! seed 0.05)
  (entity/bounce! seed 0.0)
  (world/step 300))
```

[VISUAL: The seed barely falls. The wind carries it rightward, drifting slowly down and across. It takes the full five seconds to reach the floor, swaying the whole time.]

Maximum lightness: near-zero gravity, near-maximum drag, minimal mass. The seed **floats** rather than falls.

---

## The Cannonball: Maximum Density

A cannonball is the extreme of heavy embodiment. Dense, fast, unstoppable.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((cannonball (world/spawn 'circle :x 150 :y 300 :color \"#2F4F4F\" :label \"iron\")))
  (entity/gravity-scale! cannonball 3.0)
  (entity/drag! cannonball 0.001)
  (entity/mass! cannonball 20.0)
  (entity/bounce! cannonball 0.2)
  (entity/friction! cannonball 0.5)
  (world/step 80))
```

[VISUAL: The cannonball plummets, hitting the floor in under a second. It barely bounces, settling almost immediately with a heavy thud.]

Maximum density: triple gravity, near-zero drag, maximum mass. The cannonball **crashes**.

---

## Comparing Two Tosses: The Embodiment Spectrum

We toss a stone and a scarf with the same upward impulse. The stone arcs cleanly. The scarf billows.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((stone (world/spawn 'circle :x 100 :y 150 :color \"#708090\" :label \"stone\"))
      (scarf (world/spawn 'scarf :x 200 :y 150 :color \"#FF6EB4\" :label \"silk\")))
  (entity/set-vel! stone 0 -90)
  (entity/gravity-scale! stone 1.5)
  (entity/drag! stone 0.02)
  (entity/bounce! stone 0.3)
  (entity/mass! stone 2.0)
  
  (entity/set-vel! scarf 0 -90)
  (entity/gravity-scale! scarf 0.2)
  (entity/drag! scarf 0.85)
  (entity/bounce! scarf 0.0)
  (entity/mass! scarf 0.1)
  
  (world/step 250))
```

[VISUAL: The stone traces a tight, fast parabola. The scarf rises quickly, then hangs at the apex, billowing, before drifting down slowly. Same impulse, wildly different arcs.]

The embodiment spectrum in a single frame: heavy vs light, dense vs airy, grounded vs adrift.

---

## The Falling Leaf: Oscillation and Drift

A leaf doesn't fall straight. It **tumbles**, swaying side to side as drag and turbulence nudge it.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((leaf (world/spawn 'leaf :x 150 :y 300 :color \"#7CFC00\")))
  (entity/gravity-scale! leaf 0.25)
  (entity/drag! leaf 0.75)
  (entity/bounce! leaf 0.0)
  (entity/mass! leaf 0.1)
  (letrec ((sway (lambda (t)
                   (when (< t 300)
                     (entity/set-vel! leaf (* 15 (dsin (* t 0.1))) 0)
                     (world/step 1)
                     (sway (+ t 1))))))
    (sway 0)))
```

[VISUAL: The leaf drifts down, swaying gently left and right in a sine pattern. It takes a long time to fall, tumbling the whole way.]

We add a **lateral oscillation** to the leaf's velocity every frame, simulating the effect of air currents. The result reads as **organic drift**.

---

## The Skipping Stone: Shallow Bounces

A stone skipped across water bounces low and fast, each bounce shallower than the last.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((stone (world/spawn 'circle :x 20 :y 120 :color \"#708090\" :label \"skip\")))
  (entity/set-vel! stone 120 -30)
  (entity/gravity-scale! stone 1.0)
  (entity/drag! stone 0.1)
  (entity/bounce! stone 0.6)
  (entity/friction! stone 0.05)
  (entity/mass! stone 0.8)
  (world/step 200))
```

[VISUAL: The stone bounces across the floor in low, fast arcs, each bounce slightly lower and shorter than the last, until it finally rolls to a stop.]

Shallow bounce, moderate drag, low friction — the stone **skips** rather than thuds.

---

## The Pendulum: Embodiment in Oscillation

A heavy pendulum swings slowly. A light pendulum swings quickly. Same arc length, different **period**.

```scheme
(world/reset!)

(let ((heavy (world/spawn 'circle :x 100 :y 50 :color \"#2F4F4F\" :label \"heavy\"))
      (light (world/spawn 'circle :x 200 :y 50 :color \"#FFB6C1\" :label \"light\")))
  (entity/pin! heavy 100 50)
  (entity/pin! light 200 50)
  (entity/mass! heavy 5.0)
  (entity/mass! light 0.5)
  (entity/drag! heavy 0.02)
  (entity/drag! light 0.05)
  (entity/set-vel! heavy 40 0)
  (entity/set-vel! light 40 0)
  (world/step 200))
```

[VISUAL: Both pendulums swing. The heavy one swings with slow, stately arcs. The light one swings faster, damped more quickly by drag.]

<!-- BUILD: entity/pin! for pivot-point oscillation -->

Mass affects **period** under the same force. High mass resists acceleration, making the swing feel ponderous. Low mass yields quickly.

---

## The Dropped Chain: Segmented Settle

A chain doesn't settle as one piece — each link lands and settles independently, creating a **cascade** of micro-impacts.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((links (map (lambda (i)
                    (world/spawn 'circle :x (+ 140 (* i 5)) :y (+ 250 (* i 3)) :color \"#C0C0C0\"))
                  (list 0 1 2 3 4 5 6 7))))
  (for-each (lambda (link)
              (entity/gravity-scale! link 1.2)
              (entity/drag! link 0.1)
              (entity/bounce! link 0.2)
              (entity/mass! link 0.5)
              (entity/friction! link 0.6))
            links)
  (world/step 180))
```

[VISUAL: The links fall in sequence, each hitting the floor slightly after the one before. They settle quickly, barely bouncing, piling into a small heap.]

Segmented embodiment: each part has its own settle curve. The whole reads as **jointed weight**.

---

## The Soap Bubble: Neutral Buoyancy

A soap bubble hovers, neither rising nor falling — gravity and buoyancy in perfect balance.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)
(world/wind! 10 0)

(let ((bubble (world/spawn 'circle :x 80 :y 180 :color \"#E0FFFF\" :label \"soap\")))
  (entity/gravity-scale! bubble 0.0)
  (entity/drag! bubble 0.9)
  (entity/mass! bubble 0.05)
  (entity/bounce! bubble 0.8)
  (world/step 250))
```

[VISUAL: The bubble drifts rightward with the wind, barely rising or falling. It floats in place, bobbing gently.]

Zero gravity scale is **neutral buoyancy**. The entity hangs in midair, moved only by external forces.

---

## The Tumbling Box: Rotational Drag

A box tumbles as it falls, rotational drag slowing its spin.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((box (world/spawn 'rect :x 150 :y 280 :color \"#8B4513\" :label \"crate\")))
  (entity/set-vel! box 30 -40)
  (entity/gravity-scale! box 1.0)
  (entity/drag! box 0.1)
  (entity/bounce! box 0.3)
  (entity/mass! box 2.0)
  (entity/friction! box 0.5)
  (world/step 150))
```

[VISUAL: The box tumbles as it arcs through the air, spinning as it falls. It hits the floor, bounces once, then settles with a final wobble.]

<!-- BUILD: rotational velocity and angular drag not yet wired; treating this as translational embodiment only -->

Rotational drag is like linear drag, but for **spin**. High rotational drag stops tumbling fast. Zero drag lets it spin freely.

---

## The Water Droplet: Surface Tension and Bounce

A water droplet bounces more than you'd expect — surface tension gives it a surprising springiness.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((droplet (world/spawn 'circle :x 150 :y 250 :color \"#1E90FF\" :label \"H₂O\")))
  (entity/gravity-scale! droplet 1.0)
  (entity/drag! droplet 0.2)
  (entity/bounce! droplet 0.7)
  (entity/mass! droplet 0.3)
  (entity/friction! droplet 0.3)
  (world/step 120))
```

[VISUAL: The droplet falls, hits the floor, and bounces surprisingly high. It bounces several times, each bounce smaller, before settling.]

High bounce, moderate mass — the droplet reads as **elastic**. Surface tension gives it restitution.

---

## The Pillow Drop: Soft Landing

A pillow falls slowly, high drag cushioning its descent. When it lands, it barely bounces — all the impact is absorbed.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((pillow (world/spawn 'pillow :x 150 :y 280 :color \"#FFEFD5\" :label \"down\")))
  (entity/gravity-scale! pillow 0.8)
  (entity/drag! pillow 0.6)
  (entity/bounce! pillow 0.05)
  (entity/mass! pillow 1.0)
  (entity/friction! pillow 0.9)
  (world/step 150))
```

[VISUAL: The pillow drifts down slowly, drag slowing its fall. It lands gently with almost no bounce, settling immediately.]

Soft embodiment: moderate-low gravity, high drag, near-zero bounce. The pillow **settles** rather than **lands**.

---

## The Bowling Ball: Linear and Rotational Inertia

A bowling ball rolls heavily, high mass resisting both linear and rotational acceleration.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((ball (world/spawn 'circle :x 50 :y 140 :color \"#2F4F4F\" :label \"10 lb\")))
  (entity/set-vel! ball 80 0)
  (entity/gravity-scale! ball 1.0)
  (entity/drag! ball 0.02)
  (entity/bounce! ball 0.3)
  (entity/mass! ball 8.0)
  (entity/friction! ball 0.4)
  (world/step 200))
```

[VISUAL: The bowling ball rolls across the floor, gradually slowing. High mass makes it feel **planted** — it takes a long time to stop.]

High mass, low drag, moderate friction — the ball reads as **dense and unstoppable**.

---

## The Falling Snow: A Crowd of Light Entities

Snowflakes fall together, each with identical light embodiment. The crowd reads as a **drift**.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((flakes (map (lambda (i)
                     (world/spawn 'snowflake :x (+ 50 (* i 30)) :y (+ 280 (* i 5)) :color \"#FFFAFA\"))
                   (list 0 1 2 3 4 5 6))))
  (for-each (lambda (flake)
              (entity/gravity-scale! flake 0.1)
              (entity/drag! flake 0.9)
              (entity/mass! flake 0.05)
              (entity/bounce! flake 0.0))
            flakes)
  (world/step 300))
```

[VISUAL: Seven snowflakes drift down slowly, each swaying slightly. They settle gently on the floor, a soft pile of white.]

A **crowd** with uniform embodiment reads as a single material. The whole drift feels light, airy, delicate.

---

## The Falling Hammer: Tool Embodiment

A hammer falls head-first, weighted toward one end. The center of mass shifts the feel of the drop.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((hammer (world/spawn 'hammer :x 150 :y 280 :color \"#708090\" :label \"tool\")))
  (entity/gravity-scale! hammer 1.5)
  (entity/drag! hammer 0.05)
  (entity/bounce! hammer 0.2)
  (entity/mass! hammer 4.0)
  (entity/friction! hammer 0.6)
  (world/step 100))
```

[VISUAL: The hammer drops quickly, landing with a heavy thud. The head hits first, the handle settling after. It reads as **top-heavy**.]

<!-- BUILD: per-part mass distribution for compound shapes -->

Center-of-mass shift makes a tool feel **unbalanced**. The heavy end leads.

---

## The Kicked Can: Horizontal Impulse and Settle

A kicked can skitters across the floor, bouncing and spinning before settling.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((can (world/spawn 'cylinder :x 50 :y 110 :color \"#C0C0C0\" :label \"tin\")))
  (entity/set-vel! can 100 -20)
  (entity/gravity-scale! can 1.0)
  (entity/drag! can 0.05)
  (entity/bounce! can 0.5)
  (entity/mass! can 0.4)
  (entity/friction! can 0.3)
  (world/step 200))
```

[VISUAL: The can bounces across the floor in low arcs, spinning as it goes. It gradually slows, bouncing smaller and smaller, until it rolls to a stop.]

Moderate bounce, low friction, light mass — the can **skitters** rather than slides.

---

## The Sandbag Impact: Impulse Absorption

A sandbag hanging in midair absorbs an impulse, swinging back with damped motion.

```scheme
(world/reset!)

(let ((bag (world/spawn 'rect :x 150 :y 150 :color \"#D2B48C\" :label \"sand\")))
  (entity/pin! bag 150 50)
  (entity/mass! bag 6.0)
  (entity/drag! bag 0.4)
  (entity/impulse! bag 80 0)
  (world/step 180))
```

[VISUAL: The sandbag swings rightward, slows, swings back. Each swing is smaller, damped by drag. It settles into a gentle sway.]

<!-- BUILD: entity/pin! and entity/impulse! for pivot and force application -->

High mass, moderate drag — the bag **absorbs** impulse, converting it into slow, damped oscillation.

---

## The Sliding Tray: Friction Gradient

A tray slides across a surface with varying friction — smooth at first, then rough.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((tray (world/spawn 'rect :x 50 :y 110 :color \"#8B7355\" :label \"wood\")))
  (entity/set-vel! tray 90 0)
  (entity/gravity-scale! tray 1.0)
  (entity/drag! tray 0.02)
  (entity/bounce! tray 0.1)
  (entity/mass! tray 1.5)
  (entity/friction! tray 0.2)
  (world/step 80)
  (entity/friction! tray 0.9)
  (world/step 80))
```

[VISUAL: The tray glides smoothly for the first half, then suddenly slows as friction increases. It comes to a stop much faster in the second half.]

Friction can **change** mid-motion, simulating a shift from polished wood to rough carpet. The tray's feel changes abruptly.

---

## The Cloth Drape: Maximum Drag, Minimal Bounce

A piece of cloth dropped from height drapes over the floor, settling without a single bounce.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((cloth (world/spawn 'cloth :x 150 :y 300 :color \"#F5DEB3\" :label \"linen\")))
  (entity/gravity-scale! cloth 0.6)
  (entity/drag! cloth 0.85)
  (entity/bounce! cloth 0.0)
  (entity/mass! cloth 0.3)
  (entity/friction! cloth 0.95)
  (world/step 200))
```

[VISUAL: The cloth drifts down, billowing slightly. When it hits the floor, it spreads and settles instantly, no bounce, no slide.]

Maximum friction, zero bounce, high drag — the cloth **drapes** rather than lands.

---

## The Rubber Band: Elastic Rebound

A rubber band stretched and released snaps back, oscillating with high bounce.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((band (world/spawn 'line :x 150 :y 200 :color \"#8B0000\" :label \"elastic\")))
  (entity/set-vel! band 0 -70)
  (entity/gravity-scale! band 0.5)
  (entity/drag! band 0.1)
  (entity/bounce! band 0.95)
  (entity/mass! band 0.2)
  (world/step 250))
```

[VISUAL: The rubber band bounces high, again and again, losing almost no energy. It oscillates for a long time, each bounce nearly as high as the last.]

Very high bounce, low drag — the band is nearly **lossless**. It converts kinetic energy back into height with minimal damping.

---

## The Falling Umbrella: Drag as Parachute

An open umbrella falls slowly, drag acting as a parachute.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((umbrella (world/spawn 'umbrella :x 150 :y 300 :color \"#000000\" :label \"open\")))
  (entity/gravity-scale! umbrella 0.9)
  (entity/drag! umbrella 0.92)
  (entity/bounce! umbrella 0.1)
  (entity/mass! umbrella 1.0)
  (world/step 250))
```

[VISUAL: The umbrella drifts down slowly, drag nearly balancing gravity. It settles gently on the floor with minimal bounce.]

Very high drag, moderate mass — the umbrella **floats** down, drag acting like a parachute.

---

## The Coin Flip: Spin and Settle

A flipped coin spins as it arcs, then bounces and settles on the floor.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((coin (world/spawn 'circle :x 150 :y 150 :color \"#FFD700\" :label \"coin\")))
  (entity/set-vel! coin 0 -60)
  (entity/gravity-scale! coin 1.0)
  (entity/drag! coin 0.03)
  (entity/bounce! coin 0.4)
  (entity/mass! coin 0.3)
  (entity/friction! coin 0.5)
  (world/step 150))
```

[VISUAL: The coin arcs upward, spins, falls, and bounces a few times before settling flat.]

<!-- BUILD: rotational state for spinning entities -->

Moderate bounce, low drag, light mass — the coin **clinks** when it lands, bouncing a few times before resting.

---

## The Bag of Marbles: Collective Embodiment

A bag breaks open, spilling marbles. Each marble has identical embodiment, but the **crowd** reads as a cascade.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((marbles (map (lambda (i)
                      (world/spawn 'circle :x (+ 140 (* i 8)) :y (+ 260 (* i 2)) :color \"#B0C4DE\"))
                    (list 0 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8))))
  (for-each (lambda (marble)
              (entity/gravity-scale! marble 1.0)
              (entity/drag! marble 0.05)
              (entity/bounce! marble 0.6)
              (entity/mass! marble 0.2)
              (entity/friction! marble 0.15))
            marbles)
  (world/step 200))
```

[VISUAL: Nine marbles fall in a cluster, bouncing and scattering across the floor. They settle at different times, spreading into a loose pile.]

Uniform embodiment, staggered release — the marbles read as a **spill**, each settling independently.

---

## The Pendulum Damping Test: Drag Over Time

We compare two pendulums: one with low drag, one with high. Same initial swing, different **settle time**.

```scheme
(world/reset!)

(let ((low-drag  (world/spawn 'circle :x 100 :y 50 :color \"#4682B4\" :label \"low\"))
      (high-drag (world/spawn 'circle :x 200 :y 50 :color \"#FF6347\" :label \"high\")))
  (entity/pin! low-drag 100 50)
  (entity/pin! high-drag 200 50)
  (entity/drag! low-drag 0.01)
  (entity/drag! high-drag 0.5)
  (entity/set-vel! low-drag 50 0)
  (entity/set-vel! high-drag 50 0)
  (world/step 300))
```

[VISUAL: The low-drag pendulum swings for a long time, barely losing energy. The high-drag pendulum slows quickly, settling within a few swings.]

<!-- BUILD: entity/pin! for pivot-point constraint -->

Drag is the **damping** force. Low drag means long oscillation. High drag means fast settle.

---

## The Falling Book: Flat Side Down

A book falls flat-side down, drag maximized by surface area.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((book (world/spawn 'rect :x 150 :y 300 :color \"#8B4513\" :label \"atlas\")))
  (entity/gravity-scale! book 1.2)
  (entity/drag! book 0.7)
  (entity/bounce! book 0.1)
  (entity/mass! book 2.5)
  (entity/friction! book 0.8)
  (world/step 150))
```

[VISUAL: The book falls slowly, drag slowing its descent. It lands with a soft thud, barely bouncing.]

High drag, low bounce — the book **settles** rather than crashes. Drag acts on the broad face.

---

## The Popcorn Kernel: Pop and Settle

A popcorn kernel pops upward with a sudden impulse, then settles as light, airy popped corn.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((kernel (world/spawn 'circle :x 150 :y 110 :color \"#FFFFE0\" :label \"pop\")))
  (entity/set-vel! kernel 0 -100)
  (entity/gravity-scale! kernel 0.3)
  (entity/drag! kernel 0.8)
  (entity/bounce! kernel 0.4)
  (entity/mass! kernel 0.05)
  (world/step 200))
```

[VISUAL: The kernel pops upward, floats at the apex, then drifts down slowly. It bounces lightly a few times before settling.]

The kernel starts with high velocity but low gravity scale and high drag — it **floats** more than it falls.

---

## The Anchor Drop: Maximum Gravity, Minimum Bounce

An anchor dropped into water (simulated as floor) plummets and settles instantly.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((anchor (world/spawn 'anchor :x 150 :y 300 :color \"#2F4F4F\" :label \"iron\")))
  (entity/gravity-scale! anchor 3.5)
  (entity/drag! anchor 0.3)
  (entity/bounce! anchor 0.0)
  (entity/mass! anchor 15.0)
  (entity/friction! anchor 0.95)
  (world/step 80))
```

[VISUAL: The anchor drops like a stone, hitting the floor with a heavy thud. No bounce. It settles immediately, as if embedding itself.]

Extreme gravity, zero bounce, maximum mass — the anchor **crashes** and stays.

---

## The Tossed Salad: Light Entities, Varied Embodiment

We toss a handful of lettuce leaves upward. Each has slightly different embodiment, creating a **scatter** effect.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((leaves (map (lambda (i)
                     (let ((leaf (world/spawn 'leaf :x (+ 130 (* i 10)) :y 150 :color \"#7CFC00\")))
                       (entity/set-vel! leaf (* (- i 2) 15) -70)
                       (entity/gravity-scale! leaf (+ 0.15 (* i 0.05)))
                       (entity/drag! leaf (+ 0.7 (* i 0.05)))
                       (entity/bounce! leaf 0.0)
                       (entity/mass! leaf 0.08)
                       leaf))
                   (list 0 1 2 3 4))))
  (world/step 250))
```

[VISUAL: Five leaves toss upward and outward, each arcing differently. They drift down at different rates, settling in a loose scatter.]

**Varied embodiment** within a crowd — each leaf has slightly different gravity scale and drag. The scatter reads as **organic**.

---

## The Gentle Landing: Maximum Settle Time

An entity falls and settles **slowly**, taking a long time to come to rest.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((cushion (world/spawn 'pillow :x 150 :y 280 :color \"#FFEFD5\" :label \"soft\")))
  (entity/gravity-scale! cushion 0.5)
  (entity/drag! cushion 0.5)
  (entity/bounce! cushion 0.4)
  (entity/mass! cushion 0.8)
  (entity/friction! cushion 0.6)
  (world/step 300))
```

[VISUAL: The cushion drifts down, lands gently, bounces softly several times (each bounce smaller), and takes the full five seconds to settle completely.]

Moderate bounce, moderate drag, low gravity — the cushion **eases** into rest rather than stopping abruptly.

---

## The Rolling Log: Friction and Rotational Inertia

A log rolls down a slope, rotational friction slowing its spin.

```scheme
(world/reset!)
(world/floor! 100)

(let ((log (world/spawn 'cylinder :x 50 :y 140 :color \"#8B4513\" :label \"pine\")))
  (entity/set-vel! log 70 0)
  (entity/gravity-scale! log 1.0)
  (entity/drag! log 0.05)
  (entity/bounce! log 0.2)
  (entity/mass! log 5.0)
  (entity/friction! log 0.4)
  (world/step 200))
```

[VISUAL: The log rolls heavily across the floor, gradually slowing. High mass makes it feel **ponderous**.]

High mass, moderate friction — the log **rumbles** to a stop.

---

## The Balloon Escape: Rising Until Out of Frame

A balloon rises continuously, escaping the top of the frame.

```scheme
(world/reset!)

(let ((balloon (world/spawn 'circle :x 150 :y 150 :color \"#FF69B4\" :label \"helium\")))
  (entity/gravity-scale! balloon -0.6)
  (entity/drag! balloon 0.5)
  (entity/mass! balloon 0.05)
  (world/step 300))
```

[VISUAL: The balloon floats upward steadily, slowed by drag but never stopping. It exits the top of the frame, still rising.]

Negative gravity, moderate drag — the balloon **escapes** rather than settles.

