## Exercises

Write the complete motion program for each scenario. Use the embodiment regime to make the entity **feel** right.

1. **The Glass Marble Drop**  
   A glass marble falls from 250px height onto a hard floor. It should bounce several times (high restitution), each bounce slightly lower, and settle after about 2 seconds. The marble weighs 0.4 mass units and has very low drag (it's smooth and dense). Tune gravity scale, bounce, drag, and friction until the motion reads as a **precise, glassy bounce**.

2. **The Tumbleweed Drift**  
   A tumbleweed rolls across the floor, blown by a steady 25px/sec wind. It should feel **light and airy** — low gravity scale (0.2), very high drag (0.85), almost no bounce, and low friction so it rolls easily. Spawn it at x:30 y:140 and let it drift for 4 seconds. The motion should read as **dry, hollow, wind-blown**.

3. **The Sandbag Thud**  
   Drop a sandbag from 270px height. It should fall with moderate speed (gravity scale 1.1), settle **instantly** on impact (zero bounce), and not slide at all (high friction 0.95). Moderate drag (0.3) to simulate air resistance on the fabric. Mass should be 4.0. The motion must read as **heavy, soft, and final**.

4. **The Champagne Cork Pop**  
   A champagne cork pops upward with an initial velocity of -120px/sec. It's light (mass 0.15), has moderate drag (0.4), low gravity scale (0.7), and bounces moderately (0.5). It should arc high, drift down, bounce a couple of times, and settle. The motion should feel **celebratory and light**.

5. **The Sliding Hockey Puck**  
   A hockey puck is given an initial horizontal velocity of 110px/sec at y:115 (just above the floor). It should glide almost frictionlessly (friction 0.02), with very low drag (0.01), normal gravity, and moderate bounce (0.35) in case it hits anything. Mass 0.6. The puck should **coast** for several seconds, barely slowing.

6. **The Flour Sack Flop**  
   A cloth sack of flour is tossed gently upward and to the right (velocity 40px/sec horizontal, -50px/sec vertical) from position x:80 y:160. It should feel **saggy and soft** — gravity scale 1.0, high drag (0.6), zero bounce, high friction (0.85), mass 3.5. When it lands, it should spread and settle immediately, reading as **inelastic and heavy-soft**.


---

## Notes and Additional Considerations from r1 draft

*The following material comes from an earlier or parallel revision draft (r1 draft). It is preserved here because content costs thought — nothing gets thrown away. Some passages restate the chapter's core ideas in a different voice; others introduce examples or angles not covered above. Read as supplemental exercises for the same discipline.*

### The Acceleration Gap

Light things leap to speed. Heavy things lumber. The time it takes to reach velocity is our first weight cue.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 90)
  (entity balloon
    (pos 100 300)
    (vel 0 -8)
    (accel 0 0.4)
    (radius 20)
    (color 255 200 200))
  (entity anvil
    (pos 400 300)
    (vel 0 -8)
    (accel 0 2.0)
    (radius 20)
    (color 80 80 80))
  (until (> (frame) 150)))
```

[VISUAL: Two circles rising then falling — the balloon climbs high and drifts, the anvil barely rises before dropping hard.]

The balloon fights gravity weakly; the anvil succumbs fast. Same initial upward velocity, different surrender rates.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 60)
  (entity scarf
    (pos 200 100)
    (vel 5 0)
    (accel -0.05 0)
    (radius 8)
    (color 220 180 255))
  (entity bowling-ball
    (pos 200 200)
    (vel 5 0)
    (accel -0.3 0)
    (radius 16)
    (color 40 40 40))
  (until (> (frame) 200)))
```

[VISUAL: Horizontal slide with deceleration — the scarf glides to a slow stop, the ball arrests quickly.]

Friction (modeled here as negative acceleration) grips heavier objects harder.

---


### Startup Lag

Heavy objects don't snap to full speed. They build momentum frame by frame.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 75)
  (let ((t (frame)))
    (entity boulder
      (pos 150 250)
      (vel (* 0.03 t t) 0)
      (radius 24)
      (color 100 100 90))
    (until (> t 80))))
```

[VISUAL: A circle accelerating rightward — velocity grows quadratically, so the motion feels like a heavy push gaining traction.]

The squared time term gives accelerating velocity: slow start, building speed.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 90)
  (let ((t (frame)))
    (entity marble
      (pos 150 200)
      (vel (* 0.5 t) 0)
      (radius 6)
      (color 200 200 255))
    (entity safe
      (pos 150 280)
      (vel (* 0.08 t) 0)
      (radius 20)
      (color 60 60 60))
    (until (> t 100))))
```

[VISUAL: Two objects accelerating — the marble zips away, the safe crawls into motion.]

Same linear acceleration formula, different coefficients — the safe's reluctance to move reads as mass.

---


### Overshoot and Settle

Heavy things don't stop on command. Momentum carries them past the target, then they wobble back.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 80)
  (let* ((t (frame))
         (target 300)
         (damping 0.92)
         (spring-k 0.05)
         (initial-pos 100))
    (define pos initial-pos)
    (define vel 0)
    (set! vel (+ vel (* spring-k (- target pos))))
    (set! vel (* vel damping))
    (set! pos (+ pos vel))
    (entity weight
      (pos pos 200)
      (radius 18)
      (color 80 80 80))
    (until (> t 300))))
```

*[needs: mutable state across frames — the `set!` pattern here runs once per program; full settling requires per-frame mutation]*

<!-- BUILD: wire frame-by-frame state mutation or expose a settle-spring primitive -->

Without per-frame mutation, we show the formula. A true settle loop would overshoot `target`, bounce back, and converge over dozens of frames.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 60)
  (entity puck
    (pos 200 200)
    (vel 8 0)
    (accel -0.2 0)
    (radius 10)
    (color 255 255 255))
  (until (> (frame) 100)))
```

[VISUAL: Horizontal slide — the puck decelerates uniformly, stopping cleanly with no overshoot.]

Light, low-friction object: it arrests without drama. Contrast this with a heavy pendulum that would swing past rest.

---


### Direction Change Cost

Changing a heavy object's direction costs time and energy. Sharp turns demand high acceleration; mass resists.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 90)
  (let ((t (frame)))
    (entity light-drone
      (pos (+ 200 (* 3 t)) (+ 200 (* 2 (sin (* 0.3 t)))))
      (radius 6)
      (color 150 200 255))
    (entity cargo-drone
      (pos (+ 200 (* 3 t)) (+ 250 (* 0.5 (sin (* 0.15 t)))))
      (radius 14)
      (color 100 100 100))
    (until (> t 120))))
```

[VISUAL: Two drones tracing sine waves — the light one oscillates sharply, the heavy one in lazy, wide arcs.]

Same horizontal speed, but vertical oscillation frequency differs: the cargo drone can't whip up and down.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 70)
  (let ((t (frame)))
    (entity kite
      (pos (+ 150 (* 80 (sin (* 0.1 t)))) (+ 200 (* 80 (cos (* 0.1 t)))))
      (radius 8)
      (color 255 220 100))
    (entity wrecking-ball
      (pos (+ 400 (* 40 (sin (* 0.05 t)))) (+ 200 (* 40 (cos (* 0.05 t)))))
      (radius 22)
      (color 70 70 70))
    (until (> t 180))))
```

[VISUAL: Circular paths — kite traces a wide, fast loop; wrecking ball a slow, tight one.]

The kite can afford tight curvature at speed. The ball's mass demands gentler arcs or slower rotation.

---


### Drop and Impact Anticipation

Heavy objects fall with authority. The heavier, the less air resistance delays them.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 100)
  (let ((g 0.6))
    (entity feather
      (pos 150 100)
      (vel 0 0)
      (accel 0 (* g 0.3))
      (radius 5)
      (color 240 240 255))
    (entity stone
      (pos 300 100)
      (vel 0 0)
      (accel 0 (* g 1.8))
      (radius 12)
      (color 90 90 80))
    (until (> (frame) 150))))
```

[VISUAL: Two objects dropping — feather drifts lazily, stone plummets.]

Gravity pulls equally, but drag (modeled as reduced `accel`) holds the feather back.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 85)
  (entity raindrop
    (pos 200 50)
    (vel 0 2)
    (accel 0 0.15)
    (radius 3)
    (color 100 150 255))
  (entity hailstone
    (pos 250 50)
    (vel 0 3)
    (accel 0 0.35)
    (radius 7)
    (color 200 220 255))
  (until (> (frame) 180)))
```

[VISUAL: Rain vs. hail — both accelerate downward, hail faster and with greater urgency.]

The hailstone's higher initial velocity and stronger acceleration communicate density and mass.

---


### Settle Time After Impact

When a heavy object lands, it doesn't freeze — it compresses, rebounds slightly, settles over frames.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 60)
  (let ((t (frame))
        (impact-frame 50)
        (ground-y 280))
    (entity crate
      (pos 200 (if (< t impact-frame)
                   (+ 100 (* 0.08 t t))
                   (+ ground-y (* -8 (exp (* -0.15 (- t impact-frame)))))))
      (radius 20)
      (color 120 80 40))
    (until (> t 150))))
```

[VISUAL: Crate falling then settling — after `impact-frame`, a damped exponential decay simulates rebound and settle.]

The exponential term models the bounce diminishing. A real multi-frame settle would require state mutation.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 75)
  (entity pillow
    (pos 150 100)
    (vel 0 4)
    (accel 0 0.2)
    (radius 16)
    (color 220 200 180))
  (entity kettlebell
    (pos 350 100)
    (vel 0 4)
    (accel 0 0.5)
    (radius 18)
    (color 50 50 50))
  (until (> (frame) 120)))
```

[VISUAL: Both fall — pillow drifts, kettlebell accelerates hard. The prose implies the kettlebell would *thud* and barely bounce; the pillow would *puff* and settle slowly.]

Without collision response wired, we show the fall. The reader infers the landing character from the acceleration disparity.

<!-- BUILD: wire collision + restitution coefficient for true bounce-and-settle -->

---


### Inertia in Rotation

Heavy objects resist not just linear acceleration but also spin-up and spin-down.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 80)
  (let ((t (frame)))
    (entity fidget-spinner
      (pos 150 200)
      (radius 10)
      (rotation (* 8 t))
      (color 200 100 255))
    (entity grindstone
      (pos 350 200)
      (radius 24)
      (rotation (* 0.5 t))
      (color 100 100 90))
    (until (> t 140))))
```

[VISUAL: Two spinning objects — fidget-spinner blurs, grindstone turns ponderously.]

Same time, different angular velocity. The grindstone's slow rotation communicates rotational inertia.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 70)
  (let ((t (frame)))
    (entity fan-blade
      (pos 200 200)
      (radius 12)
      (rotation (* 0.02 t t))
      (color 150 150 150))
    (until (> t 100))))
```

[VISUAL: Fan blade spinning up — angular velocity grows with *t*², slow start then faster.]

Quadratic rotation growth: the heavy rotor takes time to reach speed.

---


### Push and Resistance

A light object responds immediately to a push. A heavy one resists, then grudgingly moves.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 90)
  (let ((t (frame))
        (push-start 30)
        (push-end 50))
    (entity beach-ball
      (pos (+ 100 (if (and (>= t push-start) (< t push-end))
                      (* 2.5 (- t push-start))
                      0))
           200)
      (radius 18)
      (color 255 200 100))
    (entity boulder
      (pos (+ 300 (if (and (>= t push-start) (< t push-end))
                      (* 0.4 (- t push-start))
                      0))
           200)
      (radius 22)
      (color 90 90 80))
    (until (> t 100))))
```

[VISUAL: Both objects pushed for 20 frames — beach-ball zips forward, boulder barely budges.]

Same push duration, different displacement. The boulder's small coefficient reads as high mass.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 75)
  (let ((t (frame))
        (impulse-frame 40))
    (entity paper
      (pos (+ 150 (if (>= t impulse-frame)
                      (* 6 (- t impulse-frame))
                      0))
           200)
      (radius 6)
      (color 255 255 200))
    (entity brick
      (pos (+ 300 (if (>= t impulse-frame)
                      (* 1.2 (- t impulse-frame))
                      0))
           200)
      (radius 14)
      (color 140 80 60))
    (until (> t 120))))
```

[VISUAL: Instantaneous impulse at frame 40 — paper shoots away, brick crawls forward.]

Single-frame \"kick\" applied equally; the response reveals mass.

---


### Momentum and Coast

Once moving, heavy objects coast farther — stopping them takes sustained force.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 80)
  (entity toy-car
    (pos 100 180)
    (vel 5 0)
    (accel -0.15 0)
    (radius 8)
    (color 200 100 100))
  (entity truck
    (pos 100 240)
    (vel 5 0)
    (accel -0.05 0)
    (radius 16)
    (color 80 80 80))
  (until (> (frame) 200)))
```

[VISUAL: Both start at same velocity, different deceleration — toy-car stops quickly, truck rolls on.]

The truck's shallow deceleration slope communicates high inertia.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 70)
  (let ((t (frame)))
    (entity skateboard
      (pos (+ 150 (* 4 t) (* -0.015 t t)) 200)
      (radius 6)
      (color 100 200 255))
    (entity boulder
      (pos (+ 150 (* 4 t) (* -0.003 t t)) 260)
      (radius 20)
      (color 90 90 80))
    (until (> t 150))))
```

[VISUAL: Parabolic coast — skateboard arcs to a stop, boulder's arc is gentler, coasting farther.]

Same initial velocity, different quadratic drag. The boulder's shallow curve reads as momentum.

---


### Pendulum Swing Period

A heavy pendulum swings with a longer period than a light one of the same length — or it would, in a real physics sim. Here we *show* the period difference to communicate weight.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 60)
  (let ((t (frame)))
    (entity light-bob
      (pos (+ 200 (* 60 (sin (* 0.12 t)))) (+ 150 (* 60 (cos (* 0.12 t)))))
      (radius 6)
      (color 200 200 255))
    (entity heavy-bob
      (pos (+ 350 (* 60 (sin (* 0.08 t)))) (+ 150 (* 60 (cos (* 0.08 t)))))
      (radius 16)
      (color 80 80 80))
    (until (> t 180))))
```

[VISUAL: Two pendulums — light swings faster, heavy swings with a slower, stately period.]

In real physics, period depends on length, not mass — but animators often slow heavy pendulums to *feel* more massive.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 75)
  (let ((t (frame)))
    (entity metronome-light
      (pos 200 (+ 200 (* 40 (sin (* 0.15 t)))))
      (radius 5)
      (color 255 220 100))
    (entity metronome-heavy
      (pos 300 (+ 200 (* 40 (sin (* 0.09 t)))))
      (radius 12)
      (color 60 60 60))
    (until (> t 200))))
```

[VISUAL: Vertical oscillation — light metronome bobs briskly, heavy one sways with gravitas.]

Frequency as a weight cue: slower = heavier, in the animator's shorthand.

