### Elastic Collision Response

When two objects collide, the lighter one rebounds harder; the heavier one barely flinches.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 90)
  (entity ping-pong
    (pos 150 200)
    (vel 6 0)
    (radius 6)
    (color 255 200 100))
  (entity wall
    (pos 350 200)
    (vel 0 0)
    (radius 30)
    (color 100 100 100))
  (until (> (frame) 100)))
```

[VISUAL: Ping-pong ball approaching wall — no collision wired yet, but the reader imagines the ball bouncing back, wall unmoved.]

<!-- BUILD: wire elastic collision with mass-dependent velocity exchange -->

The *idea*: ping-pong reverses velocity sharply; wall (infinite mass) stays put.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 70)
  (entity marble-a
    (pos 120 200)
    (vel 4 0)
    (radius 6)
    (color 200 200 255))
  (entity marble-b
    (pos 280 200)
    (vel -4 0)
    (radius 6)
    (color 255 200 200))
  (until (> (frame) 80)))
```

[VISUAL: Two marbles approaching each other — equal mass, so they'd bounce symmetrically.]

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 80)
  (entity pebble
    (pos 100 200)
    (vel 5 0)
    (radius 5)
    (color 200 200 200))
  (entity boulder
    (pos 320 200)
    (vel 0 0)
    (radius 24)
    (color 80 80 70))
  (until (> (frame) 90)))
```

[VISUAL: Pebble racing toward stationary boulder — pebble would rebound hard, boulder barely shiver.]

Mass ratio determines the post-collision velocity split. No collision response wired; the setup teaches the principle.

