### Drag and Terminal Velocity

Light, high-drag objects reach terminal velocity quickly. Heavy, dense objects fall faster.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 90)
  (let ((t (frame)))
    (entity leaf
      (pos 180 (+ 50 (* 1.2 t)))
      (radius 6)
      (color 100 200 100))
    (entity acorn
      (pos 250 (+ 50 (* 3.5 t)))
      (radius 8)
      (color 120 80 40))
    (until (> t 140))))
```

[VISUAL: Constant-velocity fall (terminal velocity already reached) — leaf drifts, acorn drops fast.]

No acceleration: both at terminal velocity from frame zero. Speed difference is the weight cue.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 75)
  (let ((t (frame)))
    (entity parachute
      (pos 200 (+ 80 (* 0.8 t)))
      (radius 10)
      (color 255 100 100))
    (entity skydiver
      (pos 300 (+ 80 (* 4 t)))
      (radius 9)
      (color 100 100 200))
    (until (> t 150))))
```

[VISUAL: Two fallers — parachute descends gently, skydiver plummets until they (hypothetically) open their chute.]

Terminal velocity as a weight/drag signature.

