### Suspension and Bounce

Heavy vehicles compress their suspension more; light ones barely dip.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 70)
  (let ((t (frame)))
    (entity bike
      (pos 200 (+ 200 (* 2 (sin (* 0.4 t)))))
      (radius 8)
      (color 200 100 100))
    (entity truck
      (pos 340 (+ 200 (* 6 (sin (* 0.2 t)))))
      (radius 18)
      (color 80 80 80))
    (until (> t 150))))
```

[VISUAL: Both bouncing over rough terrain — bike oscillates shallowly and fast, truck heaves with large, slow amplitude.]

Amplitude and frequency encode suspension load. The truck's big, slow bounce reads as heavy.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 65)
  (let ((t (frame)))
    (entity skateboard
      (pos (+ 150 (* 2 t)) (+ 220 (* 1 (sin (* 0.5 t)))))
      (radius 6)
      (color 100 200 255))
    (entity loaded-cart
      (pos (+ 150 (* 2 t)) (+ 250 (* 4 (sin (* 0.25 t)))))
      (radius 14)
      (color 120 80 60))
    (until (> t 140))))
```

[VISUAL: Rolling over bumps — skateboard hops lightly, cart wallows deeply.]

Same horizontal speed, different vertical response to terrain.

