### Lifting Effort Over Time

Lifting a heavy object is a sustained effort; a light one, a flick.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 60)
  (let ((t (frame))
        (lift-start 20))
    (entity cup
      (pos 200 (if (< t lift-start)
                   280
                   (- 280 (* 3 (- t lift-start)))))
      (radius 6)
      (color 200 200 200))
    (entity anvil
      (pos 340 (if (< t lift-start)
                   280
                   (- 280 (* 0.4 (- t lift-start)))))
      (radius 18)
      (color 70 70 70))
    (until (> t 100))))
```

[VISUAL: Both objects lifted from rest — cup zips upward, anvil rises slowly.]

Lift velocity as a weight indicator. The anvil's crawl shows struggle.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 75)
  (let ((t (frame))
        (lift-duration 60))
    (entity feather
      (pos 180 (- 280 (* 0.015 t t)))
      (radius 4)
      (color 240 240 255))
    (entity dumbbell
      (pos 300 (- 280 (* 0.002 t t)))
      (radius 12)
      (color 80 80 80))
    (until (> t lift-duration))))
```

[VISUAL: Accelerating lifts — feather rises quickly, dumbbell barely budges despite effort.]

Quadratic position change (accelerating lift) at different rates.

