### Weight and Wind Resistance

Wind pushes light objects easily; heavy ones barely notice.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 85)
  (let ((t (frame))
        (wind-accel 0.3))
    (entity dandelion
      (pos (+ 150 (* wind-accel 0.5 t t)) (+ 200 (* 1.5 t)))
      (radius 5)
      (color 255 255 200))
    (entity stone
      (pos (+ 300 (* wind-accel 0.05 t t)) (+ 200 (* 2.5 t)))
      (radius 11)
      (color 90 90 80))
    (until (> t 120))))
```

[VISUAL: Both falling while drifting rightward (wind) — dandelion blown far off course, stone barely deflected.]

Horizontal acceleration from wind scaled by mass. The stone's straight drop shows weight.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 75)
  (let ((t (frame)))
    (entity scarf
      (pos (+ 200 (* 0.4 t t)) 220)
      (radius 6)
      (color 220 180 255))
    (entity chain
      (pos (+ 200 (* 0.02 t t)) 260)
      (radius 10)
      (color 80 80 80))
    (until (> t 100))))
```

[VISUAL: Wind accelerating both horizontally — scarf billows away, chain barely sways.]

Same wind force, different responses. The chain's resistance reads as mass.

