### Friction and Slide Distance

Heavy objects with high friction stop quickly; light, low-friction ones glide.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 80)
  (entity eraser
    (pos 150 200)
    (vel 5 0)
    (accel -0.25 0)
    (radius 7)
    (color 255 180 180))
  (entity ice-cube
    (pos 150 260)
    (vel 5 0)
    (accel -0.03 0)
    (radius 6)
    (color 200 230 255))
  (until (> (frame) 180)))
```

[VISUAL: Both slide rightward — eraser arrests quickly (high friction), ice cube glides far (low friction).]

Deceleration rate as a friction × weight cue.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 75)
  (entity metal-plate
    (pos 200 180)
    (vel 4 0)
    (accel -0.08 0)
    (radius 16)
    (color 120 120 140))
  (entity rubber-mat
    (pos 200 240)
    (vel 4 0)
    (accel -0.18 0)
    (radius 14)
    (color 80 80 80))
  (until (> (frame) 200)))
```

[VISUAL: Metal plate slides farther, rubber mat grips and stops sooner.]

Same initial velocity, different deceleration. The mat's quick stop reads as grippy/heavy.

