### Rebound Height After Drop

Drop two objects from the same height; the lighter one rebounds higher (given similar elasticity).

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 80)
  (let ((t (frame))
        (drop-height 100)
        (impact-frame 50))
    (entity rubber-ball
      (pos 200 (if (< t impact-frame)
                   (+ drop-height (* 0.08 t t))
                   (- (+ drop-height (* 0.08 impact-frame impact-frame))
                      (* 4 (- t impact-frame)))))
      (radius 8)
      (color 255 100 100))
    (until (> t 100))))
```

[VISUAL: Ball drops then bounces — after impact, it rises (negative velocity).]

Simplified bounce: drop phase (quadratic), then rebound (linear rise). A full sim would reverse and damp.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 75)
  (let ((t (frame))
        (impact-frame 45))
    (entity ping-pong
      (pos 180 (if (< t impact-frame)
                   (+ 100 (* 0.1 t t))
                   (- (+ 100 (* 0.1 impact-frame impact-frame))
                      (* 5 (- t impact-frame)))))
      (radius 6)
      (color 255 200 100))
    (entity bowling
      (pos 280 (if (< t impact-frame)
                   (+ 100 (* 0.12 t t))
                   (- (+ 100 (* 0.12 impact-frame impact-frame))
                      (* 1.5 (- t impact-frame)))))
      (radius 14)
      (color 50 50 50))
    (until (> t 100))))
```

[VISUAL: Both drop and bounce — ping-pong rebounds high, bowling ball barely lifts off the ground.]

Rebound velocity difference communicates mass and restitution.

