### Weight in a Lever

A heavy object on one end of a lever requires more force (or a longer arm) to lift.

```scheme
(motion
  (beat 60)
  (let ((t (frame)))
    (entity fulcrum
      (pos 250 250)
      (radius 8)
      (color 100 100 100))
    (entity lever-light-side
      (pos (+ 250 (* 80 (cos (* 0.1 t))))
           (- 250 (* 80 (sin (* 0.1 t)))))
      (radius 6)
      (color 200 200 255))
    (entity lever-heavy-side
      (pos (- 250 (* 80 (cos (* 0.1 t))))
           (+ 250 (* 80 (sin (* 0.1 t)))))
      (radius 14)
      (color 80 80 80))
    (until (> t 140))))
```

[VISUAL: Lever rotating slowly about a fulcrum — light end rises, heavy end sinks, then reverses.]

The heavy side's larger radius (and implied resistance) suggests it takes effort to lift.

